english:
  title: Dedication Text for the Beam-Raising of the Great Grain Storehouse
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heave ho, sturdy beam! A storehouse they call it—truly the wellspring of grain, the root of sustenance. In heaven it becomes a star, for the constellation mirrors the granary's form. For a nation, nothing surpasses it; its structure must be magnificent. Our kingdom has established its eternal capital, receiving tribute from all quarters. We know that grain is the weightiest concern, so we have built granaries a thousand units strong to hold our reserves. Boats arrive at the banks with their sterns linked unbroken; on land, cart wheels clatter like woven thread. Though we tax the people lightly—taking but one-tenth from the public fields—still the yearly reckoning reaches countless measures. Yet most lie exposed to the elements, their storage careless and vulnerable. What choice remained but to endure? Then came our Sage Sovereign, whose governance prioritizes the nation's wealth and whose works suit the times. Though ancients built round and square repositories to sustain ages past, none equals the wisdom of raising high walls and soaring towers. So the ministers were commanded, and the work was accomplished in mere days. One timber dragged—dust clouds a hundred leagues; one stone dropped—thunder roars across ten thousand hills. Such engineering! Such beauty! No craftsman, not even the legendary Gongyu, could improve upon it. The grain's volume? Were the reckoner Lishou himself to count, he could not finish.

    Now comes the auspicious day for the beam-raising. With reverence we strike the seven mighty tones and offer our verses of praise to all directions.

    Heave ho! The eastern beam points straight at the Dragon's horn and tail. Each spring when the Sovereign walks the field to teach the rites of tillage, we shall see the old grain turn gold with abundance.

    Heave ho! The western beam—turn and look—sees the great peaks bow down. Distant kingdoms tremble at our height: Qibin sends jade and elephant treasure; Shendu bears rhino tribute.

    Heave ho! The southern beam faces the holy mountain, where imperial fortune gathers. The people sing in contentment—see how virtuous winds dissolve their worries and blessings spread far.

    Heave ho! The northern beam commands the borderlands; the braided-haired peoples bow. Ask not how high it towers—though gold were stacked to the Northern Dipper, this storehouse would still hold more.

    Heave ho! The upper beam blots the sun and veils the mist, a hundred fathoms high. Why fear the public fields might fail to ripen? This heavenly warehouse is already overflowing.

    Heave ho! The lower beam—see how widely the gates open for ten thousand horses! Couriers ride forth across seas and lands, and all four quarters sing their songs of tribute.

    We humbly pray: After the beam is raised, may spiritual forces aid us in darkness. May blessings ripen and prosperity come. Heaven shall bring favorable seasons, earth shall yield its treasures. The three harvests grow abundant; men work the fields and women spin silk. Ten thousand people rest in peace; the granaries overflow, and the realm stands firm and eternal.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'seven mighty tones' refer to traditional ceremonial sounds used in Chinese and Korean beam-raising rituals.
  - key: ''
    value: The Dragon's horn and tail point to the Eastern Palace, symbolizing imperial governance.
  - key: ''
    value: Qibin and Shendu are ancient names for Central Asian kingdoms from which tributes were received.
  - key: ''
    value: Lishou was a legendary ancient Chinese calculator, here invoked to suggest the storehouse's immeasurable capacity.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three harvests' refers to the three seasons of agricultural production in East Asia.
  - key: ''
    value: This work celebrates the construction of a major state granary during the Goryeo dynasty, functioning as both architectural dedication and political propaganda emphasizing the kingdom's prosperity and wise governance.
